The additions definitely make it better. There still seems to be a bit lacking, but as you said, this is just a kind of 'honeymoon' period. As I had said in a previous post, I'm still a bit more interested in what's to come than what's already here. It's easier to write more than it is to doctor what's already out.

I guessed the transition from prison to outside would be a bit messy from a writing standpoint, as it seems very different to write about. I think you just have to work with it until you can nail the balance of slice-of-life and plot that there is now to deal with. I just wish I knew what was going on in your head during these events, as they're so different from what has been going on thus far.

Ultimately, I think the theme's that were present in the rehab segment need to be a bit more present. You definitely seemed to address this to some extent with the additions, such as Jake not realizing that his scarring would be shocking to those outside of the facility who hadn't seen them before.

I feel like if a bit more of these themes were worked into the story going forward, there might be a lot less nitpicks. I could already see ways to work them in, such as Jake going out onto the gym floor shirtless on compulsion, before quickly realizing his mistake but having to deal with some having seen him. Or perhaps a former sponsor option recognizes him and something happens with that.

I think even for those who aren't against Jake choosing Charlotte, that the story focus suddenly being shifted away from Jake's struggles with himself and the new society to completely about him and Charlotte and everything is just suddenly okay feels a bit disingenuous. Even if something comes up in the next chapter to address this, it feels like things have gone too smoothly. I hope that makes sense.
